{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"143e90fa-e333-4543-9a41-0e04817dd8a6","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the inspector via **npx**:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:6274`) that proxies to your server over stdio.\n\n**In the Inspector UI you can:**\n- Browse **Tools**, **Resources**, and **Prompts** your server exposes\n- Invoke tools with custom JSON inputs and see responses\n- Watch raw JSON-RPC messages in the **Messages** tab for debugging\n\n**Tips:**\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** only — any extra `Console.WriteLine` output will break the protocol. Use **stderr** for logging.\n- Pass args after `--`: `npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./Server.csproj -- --my-flag`\n- Set environment variables with `-e`: `npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector -e API_KEY=xxx dotnet run`\n- If your server is already built, point directly at the DLL: `npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet /path/to/YourServer.dll`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"15c26f3a-4909-4108-b9a3-d90a42e079f1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I can answer it directly without needing to explore any codebase.\n\nLet me provide a concise, helpful answer about using the MCP Inspector with a stdio-based C# MCP server.","outputTokens":392,"requestId":"C030:134464:1BFB17D:1F9DFC8:6A07C30B"},"id":"7e5aa83c-30fc-4019-a115-08a6ffc1b8d8","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:06:29.450Z","parentId":"6d74fb91-bb55-4e58-85d4-853ae1430138"}
